  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This study highlights the efficacy of fitness models in accurately forecasting the frequency of SARS-CoV-2 variants. With a citation count of 34 for the preprint version and 29 for the subsequent published version in PLoS Computational Biology, the work demonstrates significant academic engagement, marking its relevance in the ongoing discourse around COVID-19 variant tracking.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research titled \"Fitness models provide accurate short-term forecasts of SARS-CoV-2 variant frequency,\" released as a preprint on medRxiv before subsequently being published in a peer-reviewed journal, illustrates the authors' commitment to transparency and open science. The effective use of fitness models signifies a methodological advancement in predicting viral evolution, with the study generating a combined total of 63 citations across both the preprint and published forms, marking a substantial footprint in the academic community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Supported by prominent institutions such as the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the University of Washington, the study benefits from a strong institutional backing that validates its scientific inquiry. With citations originating from diverse countries like the United States and Sweden, the work's implications extend internationally, contributing to global efforts in epidemiological forecasting.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of public engagement indicators, such as social media mentions or discussions on community platforms, highlights a traditional academic audience for this research. However, the proven downstream reuse of 36 instances demonstrates that the findings have been instrumental in guiding further investigations, suggesting that other researchers recognize the study's value in advancing the understanding of SARS-CoV-2 dynamics.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, this research not only reinforces the significance of computational modeling in infectious disease forecasting but also emphasizes the importance of collaboration among leading institutions, thereby enhancing the collective effort to confront public health challenges exacerbated by the COVID-19 pandemic. As a peer-reviewed addition to the scientific literature, it serves as a reliable resource for subsequent studies and public health strategies.</p>",
